(Social): the presence of persons of varying backgrounds, whether by ethnicity, social status, income group, race, religion, gender, sexual orientation, national origin, native language, disability, IQ, political philosophy, opinion, geographical region, occupation, etc.  Diversity is sometimes used, mistakenly, to mean affimative action (as in "achieving diversity"), but this is an incorrect usage.  Equal employment oppotunity is a legal right.  Affirmative action is a remedy or redress for the violation of a legal right.  Diversity is the fact or condition of differences expressed or manifest in a population regardless of any rights or remedies.
(Natural): the presence of species filling the various niches of an eco-system.
(Industrial): the presence of a variety of resources of a particular type, whether as inputs or outputs of a process; or whether as alternative processes, either within an industry, or as different industries fulfilling roles within an economy.  This notion can also be applied to the securities representing different firms within an investment portfolio.